{
  "key": "accessibility",
  "title": "Accessibility Statement",
  "content": "<p> The University of Studingham is committed to ensuring that all users — including students, tutors, and administrative staff — can access and use the Portal with ease, regardless of disability or individual needs. </p> <p> We aim to provide an inclusive, barrier-free digital environment that supports accessibility, usability, and equal participation. </p> <h2>Our Accessibility Commitments</h2> <h3>1. Keyboard Navigation</h3> <p> The Portal is fully operable using a keyboard alone. </p> <p> Users can navigate through all pages and interactive elements using: </p> <ul> <li><strong>Tab</strong> – move forward through elements</li> <li><strong>Shift + Tab</strong> – move backward</li> <li><strong>Enter / Space</strong> – select or activate items</li> <li><strong>Arrow keys</strong> – navigate menus, dropdowns, and other components where applicable</li> </ul> <p> This ensures that users with mobility impairments or those who cannot operate a mouse can still use the platform smoothly. </p> <h3>2. Visual Accessibility & Colour Contrast</h3> <p> We strive to make all visual content accessible to individuals with visual impairments, including colour blindness. </p> <ul> <li>All colours used in the Portal meet or exceed WCAG 2.1 AA contrast guidelines.</li> <li> Designs are regularly tested using colour-blindness simulators (such as Sim Daltonism, Coblis, and browser-based tools). </li> <li> The interface avoids relying solely on colour to convey meaning; status indicators also include text labels or icons. </li> </ul> <h3>3. Screen Reader & Assistive Technology Compatibility</h3> <p> The Portal is structured to work with major assistive technologies used by individuals who are blind or have low vision, including: </p> <ul> <li>Speech output tools (e.g., NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)</li> <li>Text-to-speech readers</li> <li>Browser-based accessibility plugins</li> </ul> <p>Technical support includes:</p> <ul> <li>Semantic HTML structure</li> <li>ARIA labels where appropriate</li> <li>Proper heading hierarchy</li> <li>Alternative text for meaningful images</li> </ul> <p> This ensures content is understandable and navigable when read aloud. </p> <h3>4. Cognitive Accessibility</h3> <p> The Portal is designed with simple, clear, and consistent layouts to support users with cognitive or learning disabilities. </p> <p>Key features include:</p> <ul> <li>Predictable navigation patterns</li> <li>Easy-to-understand menus</li> <li>Straightforward language throughout the interface</li> <li>Clear labels, instructions, and error messages</li> <li>Avoidance of overly complex interactions</li> </ul> <p> Consistency helps reduce cognitive load and makes tasks easier to complete. </p> <h3>5. Regular Testing & Continuous Improvement</h3> <p> Accessibility is reviewed on an ongoing basis using: </p> <ul> <li>Internal audits</li> <li>Industry-standard tools (contrast checkers, simulators, keyboard testing)</li> <li>User feedback</li> </ul> <p> Improvements and updates are implemented regularly to ensure compliance with accessibility best practices and WCAG guidelines. </p> <h3>6. Feedback & Support</h3> <p> We welcome feedback on the accessibility of the University of Studingham Portal. </p> <p> If you experience difficulty accessing content, have trouble using a feature, or wish to request an alternative format, you may contact the University’s accessibility support team through the official support channels provided within the Portal. </p> <p> We aim to respond promptly to all accessibility-related concerns.</p>"
}

